The licensing check performed when assigning LICENSED_USER (or another permission that implies the LICENSED_USER) to a group will count users with mixed case usernames twice, if those users belong to a group that is already licensed.

This will manifest itself in the UI with the following error message (or similar):

{noformat}
You cannot grant this permission to group my-group as it would exceed your license limit of 10.
{noformat}

When, in fact, the operation you're performing should not breach that limit.

In the documentation:
https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Setting+up+SSH+on+Windows

we just need to generate the public key in Windows with {{ssh-keygen}} command.

I have tested that there is additional checklist need to be performed to make it work:
# Check if your public key is added to the SSH Agent:
{noformat}
$ ssh-add -l
{noformat}
# If it is not, please add it to the SSH Agent, for example:
{noformat}
$ ssh-add "C:\Documents and Settings\Username\.ssh\id_rsa"
{noformat}
# If the add part fail with the error “Could not open a connection to your authentication agent”, then run the following command:
{noformat}
cd path-to-Git/bin (for example,cd C:\Program Files\Git\bin)
bash
exec ssh-agent bash
ssh-add path/to/.ssh/id_rsa
git clone ssh://git@git-server:7999/OPEN/open-repo.git c:\git\123
{noformat}

No problems encountered. However, we recently upgraded the server that hosts our new Stash instance from PostgreSQL 8.4 to PostgreSQL 9.1, and I noted that Stash says it supports PostgreSQL 9.1 ( [https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Supported+platforms] ), however it is bundled with:

{noformat}
lib/postgresql-8.4-701.jdbc3.jar
{noformat}

The JDBC library is typically more backwards compatible than forwards compatible as it makes assumptions about how to access the schema information or how to access less standard data types such as bytea. Please consider upgrading to a more recent version of PostgreSQL JDBC to avoid problems in the future.

